1. Definition
A tree is a non-linear data structure used to store data in a hierarchical form.
It consists of nodes connected by edges.
2. Structure
The topmost node is called the root node.
Nodes connected below a parent are called child nodes.
Nodes with no children are called leaf nodes.
3. Basic Representation in C
struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node *left;
    struct Node *right;
};

Each node stores data and pointers to its left and right child nodes.
4. Applications
Used in file systems, databases, expression evaluation, and searching/sorting algorithms such as Binary Search Trees (BSTs).
